# Homework Assignment #4

![Carbon Sails by Lucie Galvin](Artwork.jpeg)
Name: Carbon Sails
Artist: Lucie Galvin (My mom, collage artist using a mix of specialty papers and everyday materials)

Questions
* Is this piece ART or CRAFT? Is it perhaps BOTH?
  * I believe this is both art and craft. There is craft involved in the skill of taking unrelated elements and piecing them together to form a coherent landscape. There is also skill in cutting the paper just so to emulate real life objects. It is art because of the way the imagination was used to create beauty and reflect a real life experience.
* What about this selection drew you to it or caught your eye?
  * This piece draws my eye through its use of texture. The main sail of the boat in the foreground is crumbled to depict it being filled with wind, and the overlaying of iridescent layers on the water portion creates the look of a shimmering sea.
* What kinds of feelings does the piece elicit when you see it?
  * This piece elicits the calm of a day by the sea and the joy that a beautiful view with a starry sky can bring.
* What do you think the artist is trying to say with the piece?
  * I think the artist is trying to preserve a treasured moment and share it with others.
* What does the piece say to YOU personally regardless of what the artist is saying?
  * This piece says to me that beauty can be found in simple scenes and that a memory can be captured abstractly through many different forms. 
* Do you think Artificial Intelligence could produce something of equal meaning?
  * I don't think AI could produce something of equal meaning. This piece of art depicts a real life view through the collection of elements that are meaningful to the artist, including pieces cut out from an advent calendar. AI can't bring the same personal and human touch to art that this piece does.
* How do you think you might apply the concept of art or craft to your software designs and coding?
  * I might apply the concept of craft by considering my designs and coding as practice towards honing a skill to be proud of. It can be art in the way that I can employ my imagination to produce something others can appreciate, whether that be through the organization of my code or the beauty of my designs.
* Do you think software creation SHOULD BE an art? Should it be a craft?
  * I think that software creation doesn't always need to be an art, but it should be a craft. I believe engineers should take pride in the quality of their work the same way a skilled craftsman would. In some cases this may lead to what I would consider art, but in some settings it may only be regarded as a good design.
* What kinds of questions do you ask yourself about your design/code? Do you go back to it after it is working and re-factor it to make it clean?
  * I ask myself whether it would be easily understood by someone else, if it makes intuitive sense. I ask if it is clean and following best standards. I go back after it is working to ensure it will continue to do so in the future, even if it needs to be passed over to someone else.

